About 10,000 workers have gone onstrike in eastern Yugoslavia during the past few days demandinghigher wages, the official Tanjug news agency said.    It said about 20 strikes broke out in the Yugoslav republicof Montenegro, triggered by falling incomes and minimum wages.More than 600 workers in the Visokogradnja construction firm atTitograd left their jobs because they had not been paid forthree months, Tanjug said.    Yugoslavia has been hit by a wave of strikes after thegovernment introduced a pay freeze in February to try to stemwage rises and almost 100 pct inflation.    Tanjug said the majority of the strikes in Montenegro werein loss making companies whose weaknesses would have led tounrest even if a wages freeze had not been implemented. Reuter&#3;